{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_fletcher_ver01/data/sn84020645/00517017851/1921010901/0104.xml":{"full_text":"iste\n\u00a9\u2022\u2022ducted from 11*5 to IMS. rorty-utgfct\nf% under th* Editorship of\nWILLIAM WALLACE dCREWg.\nT. SHEEHAN... .77. .77_7.7.......EdltUf\n\u00a9HAS. H. ALLEN...i......Publ\u00bb\u00abh\u00abr\niM Entered at Poatofflce Montgomery and Opelika\nNcond clan matter under Act of Congress Ut\n'ttarcn J. 1S7\u00bb.\n2f ember* of Anoclated Press and American News\npaper Publishers Association.\nTh- Associated Press Is exclusively entitled td the\n\u00bbe for re-publlcstion of all news credited to It Of\n\u00bb\u00abt otherwise credited in this paper and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nAll rights of re-pubitcatioa of special despatches\n7^P*te|n are also reserved.\npF-;---*\u25a0\nSS*\nps\nFull Report of\nASSOCIATED PRESS\nMORNINO ADVERTISER\nF.r Annum.fi\u00bb.M pn. Month.\u2022\nV\\El\u00ab Month.. Ml One Week.*\u00bb\nThnw Month.. i.io sintl. Copl\u00abr.\nday Edition Alone; Per Year.12.0#\nAll communications should bs addressed snd alt\n?/hion\u00aby orders, checks, etc., made psysblo to\nTHF ADVERTISER COMPANY, Montgomery. Ala.\nKELLY-SMITH CO., Foreign Representative, Lytton\nf Bldg., Chicago; 220 5th Ave., N. Y. qity.\nTHE ADVERTISER TELEPHONES:\nEubecrlption Department\u2014Plionea SSIS-SSU; Went\nDepartment\u2014Phones SPM-SPAtt; Advertising De\npartanent\u2014Phone 879S; News Department\u2014Phones\ni$. 4WM-4009; Social Department\u2014Phone JW37; AU\nW'wuss Farm Facta\u2014Phone 3773; Service. Engraving\nPhone 4073; C. H. Allen\u2014Phone *1M| W. T.\nUbeehao\u2014Phone Stfbdf K. F, Hudson\u2014Phone *W*.\n\nTHE WORK IN A BIG JOB.\nvNotwithstanding the street corner gossip\n*Al?d the newspaper stories of the wide\nspread violation of the national prohibition\n\u2018law, the Department of Internal Revenue\n'demonstrates in evidence laid before a Con\nyr gressional Committee that very earnest and\nvigorous efforts are being-put into the task\nof enforcing the, Volstead lajnr.\nThe department, which is at present\ncharged with the enforcement of the Vol\nif stead Act, is asking for an appropriation\nof $7,000,000 for the next year; Chairman\n\"\u2019\"Good, of the House Committee on Appro*\n^\u2018\u25a0priations to which the bill will go, says that\nwhen certain deficits already incurred are\nprovided Nf\u2018and certain extras added the\ni- Internal Revenue Department will require\n$9,000,000 for the specific purpose of en\nforcing the act carrying national prohibi\ntion into effect.\n|SPknl F. JlJeyer, Assistant Commissioner.\nM Internal Revenue, declared to the Con\ngressional Committee that \u201cenforcement was\ntWo toughest job any man ever went up\nagainst. The worst crooks in the world\nwere trying to beat the law and get th*\nA big profits from the illicit trade.\u201d\nThe statement given the Congressional\n.'Committee by Collector of Internal Revenue\nWilliam M. Williams, had a special interest,\nbectuse jt was the sdmmary of the first\nyear's work of his department in enforcing\nthe lank In it were contained the first fiefi.\n_ nite facte and figures as to the first year\u2019s\n\u2019\"operation of his department in enforcing\nthe law. The. efforts of the re'venue depart\nment covering the entire country wore f ar\nsons for no less than 17,665 men and worn\npan were arrested by the agents of his de\napartment for violating the law. These figures\n^.embrace only the arrests made by Federal\n-agents: the' number of violators arrested\nby State and municipal officers would in the\naggregate run much higher, but the agents\nof the revenue department bagged the\nrather considerable total of nearly 18,000\nlaw vi&tiRori;\nEven though the sum of $9,000,000\nshould be required for the task of enforcing\nthe Volstead Act the coming year, the gov\nernment would yet make money under the\noperation of the law. It was set before the\ncommittee that the government had col\nlectcd in fines and taxes the sum of $22,\n571,639 during the past year,\ni Revenue agents have destroyed\n6,830 illicit distilleries, 7,606 illicit\nstills, 3,378 still worms, 93,745 gallons\nof spirits, 40,116 fermenters, 2,712,\n012 gallons of fermented mash, 137,\n65C gallons of wine apd cider, 122,866\ngallons of spirits were seized, but not\ndestroyed.\n|v These figures reflect\u00bbthe magnitude of\nthe job of enforcing the law and they re\nflect, too, an energetic attempt to outwit\nand punish the daring and unscrupulous\nmen who are after the profits to be made\nby evadieg\u00bb the law^. Op the day Com\nmissioner Williams\u2019 statement wa\u00a7 given to\nI Congress the announcement was made in\nNew York that more than $300,000,000 of\nliquor had been brought into that city in\ntoe year by means of forged and illegal\npermits for the withdrawal of whiskey from\n$onde*d warehouses. The Federal Prohibi\ntion Commission of that district has had to\n.'arrest and prosecute a dozen of the em\nployee# of the department for accepting\n^bribes for assisting in issuing the forged\n-permits.\n\nZ D\u2019Annunzio is dead. D\u2019Annunzio is not\n\u201cdead. D\u2019Annunzio escaped Fiume in an air\n\u00a3plane and is refugeing. D\u2019Annunzio has\n^decided to remain in Fiume. Question:\n-Where is D\u2019Annunzio?\nJipi\nGovernor W. P. G. Harding, of the Fed\nir oral, Reserve Board, declares that the worst\n\u00ab>ver; we now are none too pessimistic\nf nor too optimistic. We are nearly back to\nj. normal, he tells us.\ntote-\nThat Passaic preacher\u2019s congregation\nformally forgave him his recent trans\ngressions, but the agents of the Depart\nimveii u iney arrested\nh\u00bbn\u00bb yesterday on a charge of violating the\nMann Act.\n\"k\np> Jap immigrants are not popular in the\none-star State of Texas. White immigrants\nfrom other American States give Texas all\nthe trouble it can cope with.\n\nJanuary is another one'of those off\n-season months when the telephone poles in\nAlabama sprout\nIn the recount of the Ford-Newberry\nvote, Henry gained 700 or so. Mr. New\nberry doubtless observed the increase with\ntne utmost indifference.\n|____\nA nieoe of Lord Northcliffe is to marry\nAmerican lieutenant. The young officer\nmay have visions of himself one day in the\nf act of commanding Northcliffe\u2019s army of re\nporters and printers.\nIn Ohio a man promised his wife $10\nevery time he swore, and now she tells a\nf court that he is $2,000 behind in his pay.\nments. He is not only a cusser,- but a\nfibber and a fraud.\nv\"\u2018 v.\n\u2022X-:?* if LET UNCLE SAM DO IT.\nThe Federal Trade Commission, after in\nvestigating tW mfcrketing problems of the\ncountry, thinks it k^ows what ia needed to\n\u25a0o've these problems. The F. T. C. calls\nfor the creation of Federal markets in all\ndistributing centers and a Federal licensing\nsystem with water-tight Federal regula-.\ntion. The Commission declares that State\nand municipal authorities lack adequate\npower to regulate the handling of food sup\nplies, and although if the State and Munici\npal authorities should co-operate they might\nWork out the marketing problems, the Com\nmission believes this plan would not prove\nspecially efficacious.\n\"May be so,\u201d comments the Chicago\nTribune. \u201cBut wouldn\u2019t it'be worth while\ntw. give it a trial before adding more com\nplicated duties to the tremendous tasks of\nthe centra] Government?\u201d\nThe Tribune voices its impatience at this\ncharacteristic recommendation of the Trade\nCommission. It is an impatience shared,\ntoo, by a growing number of thoughtful\npeople, everywhere. The Tribune says:\nPower seeks more power. About\n\u00ae7\u00abry Federal agency is pressing on\nall possible occasions for an expansion\nof its own functions and an increase of\nits powers. Impatient reformers with\neager eyes for evils to be cured and\nvision extending to the end of their\nnoses are always running to Washing\nton to get their particular plaster\npasted on the body politic. It\u2019s spec\ntacular and comparatively simple.\nMeantime there n no organised resist\nance in the interest of local initiative,\nlocal authority, local autonomy.\nThe result of this tendency will, of\ncourse, be the complete ruin of our\nAmerican system of balanced central\nand local functions. It will be the\ngrowth of a central machine so com\nplex and ponderous as to\" be not only\ninefficient but paralyzing. Political\npower will mass about it. Bureaucracy\nwill fossilize government. Federal\nregulation will spread into all activi\nties and dominate them wherever possi\nble. Eten in a comparatively small\ncountry, like France, centralization has\nbeen an evil of first rank. In this great\ncountry it would be worse than the\nplagues of Egypt.\nEvery proposal for an increase of\nFederal functions and Federal power\nshould be compelled to establish at\nleast a strong prima facie case for it\nself. It should never be accepted un\ntil the inadequacy of alternatives has\nbeen demonstrated. The viewpoint of\nthe trade commission is not this. It\nvirtually assumes the failure of local\nauthority and .proposes to go direct-to\nFederal regulation. This is the easy\nshort cut which theoretic reformers\nlike. We have yet to find one who has\nany respect for American principles of\ngovernment or any regard for the\npreservation of the system of balance\nfounded by the wise men who made the\nconstitution.\nThfe city of Washington and the treasures,\nactual and potential which it contains, con\nstitute the great American Good Thing. It\nis a peculiarity of the tribe of bureaucrats\nand assistants who attach themselves to\nthe Federal payroll, to become prophets of\nthe Federalistic point of view. It is worth\nwhile to remember this truth, that as soon\nas men get on the payroll at Washington,\nmost of them come to think in Federal\nterms. The District of Columbia is their\nwhole world, the outlying districts being\nmerely provinces against which levies for\nfunds shall be made, from time to time.\nPerhaps this is natural. For it is true that\nas Federal departments and bureaus multi- 1\nply and increase their power and ramifica\ntions, the officials and employees already\nthere see themselves become better en\ntrnched, more secure. In 'a very definite\nsense it is to the interest of the official\ntribe to increase its numbers and to in\ncrease the need for numbers and money.\nFor that reason alone we should scrutinize\ncarefully the discoveries and pronuncia\nmentoes of professional officialdom. Every\npetty bureau in Washington is loyal to the\ntribal interests and eager to see tribal\ndomains enlarged.\nThe tribal chiefs and petty chiefs at\n'Washington never want for organized sup\nport in the provinces. The number of per\nsons in each province who could find it\nconvenient to remove on short notice 4o\nWashington is large, much larger than it\nshould be. They help to create the imaginary\nneed for their services. And it pays to\nhelp the cause:\nThen, too, Washington symbolizes the\nwealth and power of the Nation; and\ncuriously enough it still symbolizes to many\npeople efficiency in administration and\noriginal wisdom in prophecy as well as\nspecial and exalteA virtue. Washington is\neasy to reach by rail or telegraph. The\npowers to be consulted are isolated and\neasy of access Not many men in Wash\nington need to be converted to an idea to\nput it through. And so the ambitious,\njoined by the zealots, march upon Wash\nington with the assurance that their work\nwill be easy. They go to Washington and\ndemand the further extension of adminis\ntrative powers, the increase of old appro\npriations and the passing of new appropria\ntions, all of which, incidentally calls for\n-the addition of another army of employees.\nAll of which makes payday for the tax\ngiver a merry hour in his troubled life.\nAnd it makes, too, for the creation of .a\nclumsy monster of Federalism that gluts it\nself upon the substance of the people, feeds\nslowly upon their liberties, and gives little\nin return.\nWHO DIO IT 7\nWho killed Cock Robin? It mu3t have\nbeen th\u00a3 Democratic party, for the party, if\nyou listen to a Republican, has been guilty\nof everything el^e; the killing of Cock\nRobin would have been only in keeping\n.with the destructive policies of the Demo\ncrats.\nA prosperous Republican business man.\na gentleman who is interested iti the wool\nbusiness and who no doubt made much\nmoney during the war, declared before a\nSenate Committee Friday that the Demo\ncratic administration was responsible /or\nthe collapse in prices and for the attend\ning \u201cbuyers strike.\u201d He specifically charged\nthat the wholesale, general charges of At\ntorney-General Palmer as' to profiteering,\nhad undermined public confidence in the'\nmen engaged in business and had precipi-*\ntated the present financial collapse/\nTrusting to a more or less reliable\nmefnory we can recall that Colonel Wood,\nthe gentleman in question has appeared\n\nmore than once in the news of the day as\nthe representative of the woolen manufac\nturing interests in Washington. His\nclients have ridden high under the various\nRepublican tariffs, but they have had\nsmaller profits under .the present Under\nwood Tariff Act.\nThe gentleman\u2019s state. of mind has its\nown interest at this time, as he attacks the\nDemocratic administration. He is the\nrepresentative of a rather wealthy and a\nvery influential class of American citizens,\nfinanciers and business men. If we under\nstand their statd of mind we can appreciate\nanew the moving causes which were behind\ntheir generosity to the Republican cam\npaign committee last year, the bitterness\nwith which they fought the Democratic\nticket and the enthusiasm which they mani\nfested for ait old-fashioned Republican.\nThey hate the Democratic administration\nwith a deadly burning hatred. Their posi\ntion is that the present administration has\nwaged consistent warfare on what is com\nmonly called the business interests of the\ncountry, and that it used the prestige of\nits official power to discredit the men who\nconduct American business. We need hot\nbelieve as they believe or to sympathize\nw\u2019th them in their unreasoning hatred of\nthe Democratic party, to realize that this is\na dangerous class fo antagonize in national\npolitics, once it has become solidified by\nhate, prejudice, or regret over lost profits.\nSince the election, and flushed with vic\ntory,^the representatives of this class have\nnow come out in the \u25a0open. The specific at\n^ick on the administration lies in the charge\nmat the foolish and unwise policy of de\nstroying confidence in business men' had\nprecipitated the present marked depression\nin business. Now1 let us see about that.\nEvery economist knew that thd inflated\nbusiness condition of a year ago, the orgy\nof extravagance, the pra of* high prices\nwould inevitably end in a panic, or rather\n,n what would be as near a financial panic\nas the country could have wfth the Federal\nReserve system in operation. Such an-end\nwas certain and inevitable. It was inevit\nable, although we did not see it at that\ntime, that \u2018\u2018a* buyers\u2019 strike\u201d would be in\naugurated. Whether the official pronounce\nments of the government helped to precipi\ntate the .reaction, and brought it about too\naapidly is a question open for debate. If\nit could have come mdre slowly, it would\nhave been infinitely better for the country,\nbut it came with a precipitate rush.\nAbout the wisest thing said at that com\nmittee meeting even though it did not seem\nrelated to the subject under discussion, was\nthe declaration of Senator Thomas, \u201cOne\nman is very willing to see another lose\nmoney, but is not anxious to lose any him\nself.\u201d\nROMANCE AND ADVENTURE.\nMillions of people are watching with a\nkeen interest for any news of the three\nballoonists who, aft,er a sensational flight of\nmore than fifteen hundred miles from\nRockaway, N. Y., to a remote spot in\nthe Canadian wilds, are now making their\nway painfully throuj|h the snow back to\n^civilization. We may be sure that the news\npaper reader, and the American people\nare a nation *of newspaper readers, turns to\nno item in the paper njpre eagerly than he\ndoes to the latest word the Associated\nPress has to record of the three men who\nfell with their balloons, almost beyond the\nconfines'of civilization.\nThe explanation of the great popular in\nterest in the balloonists is simple. They\nare men marked for popular imagination\nbecause of adventure and danger. The at\nmosphere of romance is about them. It is\nno tax on the imagination of the average\nman to picture the flight of the balloon\nfrom Rockaway, bk Y._the terrifying\nIjours in the air whe'n the balloon was\ncaught by a gale and swept to the north\nwest, the final descent in a wilderness of\nsnow and forests without a sign of human\nbeing or a human habitation in sight, the\nterrible struggles through the snow in an\naimless search for help until almost fam\nished and helpless they come upon a soli\ntary Indian who leads them to Moose Fac\ntory,. an outpost of civilization. Danger\nwas there and in plenty and in every part\nof their journey. The world watches with\nimpatience their appearance in civilization\nto receive the adulation which comes to the\nadventurer and the man who braves dan\nger.\nGovernor Hardee, of Florida, recently\ninaugurated, bears a good ofd Southern\nname.\nou can\u2019t hide behind a woman\u2019s skirts\nthese dcys._\nBaltimore has launched a better boys\ncampaign, as if-boys would not be boys.\nNow that Theobald von Bethmann-Holl\nweg is dead maybe the papers will cease to\nmissnell\nBUILDING BOOM TO LEAD THE WAY.\nSelma Times-Journal.\nIt is believed that the first \u201cbreak\u201d in the\nwidespread business tie-up will come in a\nrevival of building activities. The facts of\na universal house shortage are undeniable,\nalthough there have been alterations and'\nrenovations of properties on a wide scale\nsn ar. effort to meet the acute conditions.\nIf prices of building materials and labor\nere reduced sufficiently the demand for\nhouses should come into play, and it is be\nlieved will act as a suong compelling force\nfor more active trade. Students of cur\nunusual economic situation are agreed that\nthe \u201clead off\u201d in the business revival will\nbe taken by the building agencies, as the\nworld's housing-facilities are almost tragical\nly inadequate. It is believed that construe\nlive work to meet this -keenly felt publx\nneed cannot be put off much longer.\nAccording to a survey made by the\nUnited States Chamber of'Commerce there\nis-now a shortage of 1,250,000 dwellings in\nthis country, which means that more than\n4,000,000 persons are improperly or in\nadequately housed today. There is not a\ntown in the country that is not short of\nfactory, office or dwelling structures In\naddition there is not a railroad that does\nnot need more engines, more cars, or new\nrails 'or new bridges. There is hardly a\npublic road that does not need repairing.\nUncle Sam, all over, has an immense job\nahead of him. Is it not about time he and\nhis gang got busy on it? The way to do a\nthing that has got to be done is to get to\nwork and do it\nyiiWioo \u25a0Jv\\onrv<Lornfrj\n3\u00aer norfl^omrr'j'\nTrt* cntnr\nUNHlttHEl)\n==d >\\\u00a3Rt COME\ntVTftpcrnesi\nIn/ll'\nVKriKEHi CkRClE\nG|0\\nC* IK*o\n__..I __.\nSOWt^WMCi 4giOuK>\nfct PONE Rbouf if.\nf3S\u00bbgg- m\n\u2019iHe FoUNtRIrt\n\"DON-*\nCH\u00bbT*C\nnw\nLetters To Editor\nWHAT SHOULD BE THE INDIVIDUAL\u2019S\nBUYING POLICY?\nEditor The Advertiser:\nI was very much interested in the article\nwhich I am herewith quoting, since it vitally\ni oncerns present day business and recon\nstruction. I believe that it is pertinent\nboth to merchant and customer, and will be\nappreciated by thinking people that read it.\nRealizing that they have been living\nthrough three years of a riotous spending\norgy, Americans are waking up to the fact\nthat thei*- dream of perpetual war pros\nperity could be nothing more than a dream.\n'But, the awakening has beer, so Budden\nand the realization has been so shockingly\ntrue that, in tiding to correct a deceiving\nevil, folks went to the other extreme of\ncutting their expenditures to the bone,\nwhich is equally mistaken and equally in\njurious, not only to business, but to the\nrank and file of the people as well, be\ncause any false tightening up in buying is\ngomg to mean unemployment and lower\nwages just as surely as the other extreme\nov riotous buying forced prices up to the\nextraordinary and unnatural levels of the\npeat few years.\nMind you, this is not a plea for a return\nto wild extravagance. On the contrary,\nit is an argument against extreme retrench\nment and for the maintenance of a normal.\nbuying policy.\nMan\u2019s common judgment tells him that\nuninterrupted business depends upon his\ncontinued buying, that his ability to buy de\npends upon his continued employment and\nt.\u2019.at employment depends upon normal busi\nness.\nBy the public persisting in putting' off\nthe purchase of even seasonable necessities,\nit fergets the connecting link to an endless\nchain of harm which not only affects Ameri\ncan business, but more seriously affects\nthe general public.\nWhen the public stons buying, stocks be\ngin to accumulate, ojd orders given to\nmanufacturers are cancel)^ and new. ones\npjstppned. Thus the manufacturer, face to\nface with on increasing inventory and de\nclining demand, begins to cut production,\nays off help and cuts wages. And these em\n\u2022flThyees. in turn, with their incomes shut\neff or reduced, add that much more to the\ndecline in buying which inevitably spells\nbusiness depression.\nEvery American citizen, mindful of his\nown best interests will not yield to the\npresent temper of postponed buying. He\nWill be economical and thrifty, but he will,\nas well, keep right on investing in season\nab*e or staple goods that are necessary or\nderivable in the daily enjoyment of life and\nlving.\nPricea of wearing apparel and shoes,\nhave now reached arnoint below which they\nwill not dropiunless disaster actually over\ntakes the country.\nThe .nan who buys now not only favors\nh'<: purse, but puts much-needed money in\ncirculation. He helps to revive trade and\nputs an end to the mounting unemploy\nment.\nThrough our head-long extravagance in\nthe war-period we produced an unwhole\nsome business condition of which profiteer\ning was but one of the by-products. But, let\nus not make the even more serious error\nnow, and, by rushing to the other extreme,\ncreate a condition of unemployment and at\ntending \u201chard times\u201d that gouge the aver\nage citizen more surely than any brand of\nprofiteering ever did.\n\u201cBuy now,\u201d and you will lighten the\nexisting business depression and help in\ndustry, commerce and -etail trade oii<the\nup-grade in the new year.\n\u201cBuy now.\u201d\nVery truly,\nE. PRINTICE.\nWHITE COUNTIES AND THE CENSUS.\nEditor The Advertiser:\nThe United States census for 1920 shows\nseveral interesting agricultural develop\nments in Alabama, from 1910 to 1920. The\nmost important of these were ^he boll\nweevil invasimi and^the consequent diversi\nfication of crops. The following figures\nshow the increases in population in the\n\"jjrober of farms and in virtue from 1910 to\n1920, in nihe white counties, six in the\nwiregrass\" and three in South Alabama:\nBaldwin: Increase in population, 2,552;\nincrease in farms, 304; increase in value.\n$3,172,399.\nConecuh: Increase in population, 3,160;\nincrease in farms, 122; increase in value,\n$2,345,913.\nCoffee: Increase in population, 3,951; in\ncrease in farms, 954; increase in value.\n$6,688,238.\nCovington: Increase in population, 5,979;\nincrease in farms, 931; increase in value,\n$6,628,092.\nDale: Increase in population, 1,103; in\ncrease in fatms, 10;,increase in value. $3.\n890,776.\nEscambia: Increase in population, 3,573;\nincrease in farms, 392; increase in value,\n$2,690,307.\nGeneva: Increase in population^ 3,085;\nincrease in farms, 720; increase in value,\n$8,095,432.\nHouston: Increase in population, 4,920;\nincrease in farms, 311; increase in value,\n$6,647,526.\nPike: Increase in population, 816; in\nc-easfc in farms, \u00a37 increase in value', $4,\n3C0.131.\nTotal; Increase in population, 28,439; in\ncrease Ai farms, 3,748; increase in value1\n$44,41fA0ql.\nThe total value of farms in t|iese nine\ncounties in 1910 was' $33,156,013, and in\n1920 it was $82,575,028. an increase of\n$44,419,015, or 11? per cenf.\nIn all of these counties, except Baldwin,\ntrorn the termination of the civil war in\n1865, to the invasion of thp boll weevil,\ncotton was the principal crop.\nWith the advent of the boll weevil the\ndiversification of crops was inaugurated\nwith the remarkable increase in the value\nof farms.\nProbably in no two counties of the State\nhas diversification been developed as much\nas in Coffee and Geneva counties. 1\nIn 1910 the value ot farms in Coffee'was\n$4,492,901, and in 1920 it was $11,539,\n139, an increase of $6,588,238, or 140 per\ncent. The value of farms \u2018in Geneva in\n1910 was $4,450,784, and in 1920 it was\n$12,546,217, an increase of $8,095,433, or\n180 per cent.\nAll of these counties show increases in\n-population, in the number of farms, and\nin the value of farms. The increase in the\nvalue of farms is more than twice the in\ncrease in Black Belt counties.\nThese figures show more eloquently than\nwords the effect of diversificatidh of crops\ni.i increasing the value of farms.\nThese figures also show that the only\nmethod for agriculture in Alabama to ob\nta*n its highest development, is the reduc\ntion of cotton Acreage, the diversification\nr\nf\nof cropaj stock raising and raising all hotne\nsupplies.. P\nThis is the true- Solution of the problem\nthat confronts our farmers.\nw f J. T. GORMAN, i\nMobile, Ala., Jan. 7th, 1921.\nRussia\u2019s Peasants\nJohn A. Gade, in The North American Re\nview.\nThe peasants of Russia, some hundred\nand thirty-five million of them, live so in\ndependently and isolated, scattered through\nout the vast plains and boundless forests,\nthat they have no knowledge of or interest\n:n the doings of the great industrial centers.\nThey bother their heads little about the end\nless ordinances.\nTo a certain extent the peasants are\nbetter off than they were,b%fore. They cei-\ntamly have many piore comforts and the*\nare not starving as are the citf folfc. The\nimprovement in their lot,they do not owe to\nthe boishevik, but to the revolution which\npreceded and resulted in the all-Russian\nconstituent assembly. This, and not the\nsoviet government, declared t*,\u201cThe use of\nal, lands mines forests and Waters is free\n.o all citizens of the Russian republic re\ngardless of nationality or creed\nVred robbers\u2019- system,\"by which the soSrt\ngovernment redistributed the land, allowed\nthe most powerful to seize the lion\u2019s share.\nOf course they have changed their modes\nof living. They grow no more flax, Wheat\nor vegetables than what is needed for their\nwants, and of that they bury in the safest\nplace all but the smallest quantity. Prowl\nmg and requisitioning commissars and gov\nernment agents have until now forced them\nat the point of the bavonet to give ud all\nthe surplus they could find. All their\nh-.rses and cows have been taken cxcent a\nsingle one. It was obedience or the bullet\nThe peasants have either themselves\nseteed the land of their old masters or land\nlords, or had it doled out to them bv the\ngovernment, which has retained Some four\nper cent, for communist uses. In either\ncase, they are very uneasy as to their title,\nand, valuing land aboye all else..are most\nanxious to hand it on to their chifdr-n\nThe government has not vet felt suffi\nciently strong to tell them outright that it\nis not theirs to have and to hold, as all land\nhas been nationalized and belongs to the\ngovernment. They loathe service in the\nred- armies, fighting where they have no\ngrudge and in regiments filled with political\nagents, the very commander subject to the\norders of the commissar accompanying\nevery regiment. The political education\nback of the lines bored them to death. I\nhave read .many vof their letters taken out\nof captured mails, and it was always the\nsame story.\nThey could feel the necessity of fighting\nagainst the white armies when they were\ntold that these would, if victorious, merely\nbring back the old, reactionary days They\nwould also gladly fight against the old arch\nenemy, Poland.\n4\nThe Difference.\nBaltimore American.\n\u201cThere is one resnect in which a live\nbusiness man isn\u2019t like u tree.\u2019\u2019\n\u201cWfiat is that?\u2019\u2019\n\u201cIf he remains rooted to the spot, he\ncan\u2019t branch out.\u201d\nv;","height":"28156","width":"19672"}}
